  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>If you own a unit or townhouse in Brisbane and you are preparing to sell, the body corporate manager is one of the first people you will need to contact. Most sellers in freestanding houses have never dealt with one. If this is your first unit sale, understanding the BCM's role early will save you time, avoid surprises during the contract period, and help you present your property with confidence.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who the body corporate manager is</h2>
      <p>A body corporate manager is a licensed professional or management company appointed by the body corporate committee to handle the day-to-day administration of a community titles scheme. In Queensland, community titles schemes are the legal structures that govern units, townhouses, and most apartment buildings. The BCM is not a property manager. They do not manage individual lots or tenants. Their client is the body corporate itself, not any individual owner.</p>

      <p>In larger buildings, the BCM might be a dedicated strata management company with staff assigned to the scheme. In smaller complexes of four to eight lots, the role is often handled by a sole operator or a boutique firm. Either way, they are the administrative hub for the scheme and the people who hold the records you will need for your sale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the body corporate manager does</h2>
      <p>The BCM is responsible for a wide range of administrative functions. They maintain the body corporate roll, which records each owner's details and lot entitlements. They issue levy notices and collect administration fund and sinking fund contributions from all lot owners. They arrange the building insurance for common property, manage claims when damage occurs, and hold the certificate of currency.</p>

      <p>The BCM organises and minutes the annual general meeting and any committee meetings during the year. They maintain the body corporate's financial records, prepare annual budgets, and manage both the administration fund (day-to-day expenses) and the sinking fund (long-term capital works). They coordinate maintenance of common property areas and engage contractors on behalf of the committee.</p>

      <p>They also maintain records of by-laws, any exclusive use agreements affecting individual lots, and correspondence with the committee. All of this creates the paper trail that a buyer's solicitor will inspect during due diligence.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the body corporate manager does not do</h2>
      <p>The BCM is not responsible for anything inside your individual lot. Defects within your unit, your hot water system, your air conditioning, your internal plumbing: all of these are your responsibility, not the BCM's. If a buyer's building inspector identifies a problem inside the unit, that is a matter between you and the buyer, not something the BCM can resolve.</p>

      <p>The BCM also does not manage tenancies. If your unit is tenanted, you need a separate property manager for that relationship. And the BCM does not set or enforce sale prices or terms. Their authority is limited to the common property and the scheme's administrative obligations.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why sellers need the body corporate manager</h2>
      <p>There are two documents that come from the BCM and that every unit sale in Queensland requires. The first is the body corporate disclosure statement. Under Queensland law, a seller of a lot in a community titles scheme must provide a disclosure statement to the buyer before contracts are exchanged. This document includes key information about the body corporate: current levies, the existence of any by-laws affecting the lot, any exclusive use agreements, and whether the scheme is subject to any proceedings or investigations.</p>

      <p>The second is the body corporate records search. A buyer's solicitor will almost always order a full records search as part of their due diligence. This is an inspection of the scheme's financial and administrative records, typically covering two years of AGM and committee meeting minutes, the current balance of the administration and sinking funds, the insurance certificate of currency, details of any current or pending legal proceedings, outstanding levies on any lots, any current or proposed special levies, and the by-laws of the scheme. The buyer typically pays for this search, but sellers who order their own records search upfront are better placed to price and present their property accurately.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to request the disclosure statement</h2>
      <p>Contact the BCM early in your pre-sale preparation. You will need to provide your anticipated settlement date so they can issue the disclosure statement with current information. The BCM charges a fee for preparing this document, typically between $200 and $400 depending on the size and complexity of the scheme. They generally need 5 to 10 business days, so do not leave this until the week before you want to sign contracts.</p>

      <p>If you are working with a solicitor or conveyancer to prepare your contracts, they will coordinate with the BCM on your behalf. Either way, initiate the request before your listing goes live so the disclosure statement is ready when a buyer is ready to sign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to ask the body corporate manager before listing</h2>
      <p>As a lot owner you have the right to access the body corporate's records. Before you list, use that access to understand what a buyer's solicitor will find. There are three questions worth asking directly.</p>

      <p>First, are there any pending or proposed special levies? A special levy is an additional charge raised on all owners, typically to fund a major unplanned expense such as a lift replacement, waterproofing works, or structural repairs that the sinking fund cannot cover. If a special levy is being considered, buyers will discover it in the records search and may use it to renegotiate price or withdraw. Knowing about it before you list lets you price accordingly or decide whether to pay it out before settlement.</p>

      <p>Second, is the scheme involved in any legal proceedings or disputes? Active litigation involving the body corporate is a material disclosure obligation. It can also deter buyers who do not want to purchase into an ongoing legal matter.</p>

      <p>Third, what is the current state of the sinking fund? A well-funded sinking fund indicates the scheme is financially healthy and that future capital works can be covered without special levies. A deficit in the sinking fund is a risk flag for buyers and their solicitors. A healthy balance is a selling point worth knowing and communicating.</p>

      <p>The BCM's records are accessible to all lot owners at any time. Smart sellers review them before their buyers do.</p>

